As already mentioned you can do this utilizing [Regular Expressions](https://www.vogella.com/tutorials/JavaRegularExpressions/article.html) (RegEx). Here is an example of carrying out this task using different Regular Expressions along with the [String#split()](https://www.javatpoint.com/java-string-split) and the [String#replaceAll()](https://www.javatpoint.com/java-string-replaceall) methods:

    //String line = &quot;SG75J6: Dark Brown 2200 x 75 x 24.5 12.3&quot;;
    String line = &quot;NG6083: Grey Window 2500 x 63.5 x 17.2 13.4&quot;;
    //String line = &quot;NG6083: Red 2500 x 63.5 x 17.2 13.4&quot;;
        
    String[] duom = line.split(&quot;\\s{0,}:\\s{0,}&quot;);
    String gamintojas = duom[0];
        
    String pavadinimas = duom[1].split(&quot;-?\\d+(\\.\\d+)?&quot;)[0].trim();
        
    String numericals = duom[1].replaceAll(&quot;[a-z A-Z]{1,}&quot;,&quot; &quot;).trim();
    String[] numericalArray = numericals.split(&quot;\\s+&quot;);
    try {
        double ilgis = Double.parseDouble(numericalArray[0]);
        double plotis = Double.parseDouble(numericalArray[1]);
        double aukstis = Double.parseDouble(numericalArray[2]);
        double kaina = Double.parseDouble(numericalArray[3]);
        
        // Display the results...
        System.out.println(&quot;gamintojas equals:  &quot; + gamintojas);
        System.out.println(&quot;pavadinimas equals: &quot; + pavadinimas);
        System.out.println(&quot;ilgis equals:       &quot; + ilgis);
        System.out.println(&quot;plotis equals:      &quot; + plotis);
        System.out.println(&quot;aukstis equals:     &quot; + aukstis);
        System.out.println(&quot;kaina equals:       &quot; + kaina);
    } catch (Exception ex) {
        // Do whatever you want here!
        System.out.println(&quot;Whoops! A Double.parseDouble() Error!&quot;);
    }

**What do the Regular Expressions mean:**

&gt; **String[] duom = line.split(&quot;\\\\s{0,}:\\\\s{0,}&quot;);**

&gt; **String gamintojas = duom[0];**

Split the string in **line** based on any Colon (**:**) found within the string ***even if*** it has one or more white-spaces ***before OR after*** the colon. The **duom** Array variable now contains 2 elements:

    At Element 0: &quot;NG6083&quot;
    At Element 1: &quot;Grey Window 2500 x 63.5 x 17.2 13.4&quot;

We now take the first element (**duom[0]**) and place it into the **gamintojas** variable.

&gt; **String pavadinimas = duom[1].split(&quot;-?\\\\d+(\\\\.\\\\d+)?&quot;)[0].trim()**

Split the string contained within the 2nd element of the **duom** Array variable (duom[1]) based on string representations of signed or unsigned Integer or Double numerical values but accept only the first element ([0]) of that split and trim any possible white-spaces from it. The pavadinimas variable now contains:

    &quot;Grey Window&quot;

&gt; **String numericals = duom[1].replaceAll(&quot;[a-z A-Z]{1,}&quot;,&quot; &quot;).trim();**

Create a String (**numericals**) to hold all the numerical values contained within the 2nd element of the **duom** Array variable (duom[1]) as white-space delimited string using the [String#replaceAll()](https://www.javatpoint.com/java-string-replaceall) method. The RegEx used in the **replaceAll()** method will replace all characters (1 or more) which are &#39;a&#39; to &#39;z&#39; or &#39;A&#39; to &#39;Z&#39; or white-spaces and replace them with a single white-space (&quot; &quot;). The replacement is then trimmed of leading and trailing white-spaces right away. The **numericals** string variable will now contain:

    &quot;2500 63.5 17.2 13.4&quot;

&gt; **String[] numericalArray = numericals.split(&quot;\\\\s+&quot;);**

This line creates a String Array named **numericalArray** by splitting the newly created **numericals** variable based on **one or more** (should there for some reason be more) white-spaces. The elements contained within the **numericalArray** String Array will look like:

    At Element 0: &quot;2500&quot;
    At Element 1: &quot;63.5&quot;
    At Element 2: &quot;17.2&quot;
    At Element 3: &quot;13.4&quot;

Now it&#39;s just a matter of parsing each element of the **numericalArray** array into its respective ***double type*** variables using the [Double.parseDouble()](https://www.tutorialspoint.com/java/lang/double_parsedouble.htm) method and then displaying the results.

The parsing is housed within a [try/catch](https://www.w3schools.com/java/java_try_catch.asp) block just in case a ***NumberFormatException*** is thrown for some reason.

